***************************************************************************
University World News was the official media partner to the Unesco World
Conference on higher education, held in Paris from 5-8 July 2009.
***************************************************************************
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
NEWS: Our correspondents worldwide report
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

MALAYSIA: Accused N igerian students deported

Tunde Fatunde
The Malaysian government has deported two N igerian postgraduate students
who were among 10 people from various countries detained in January for
alleged links with the terrorist organisation Al-Qaeda. The N igerians had
been studying at the International Islamic University near the capital
Kuala Lumpur.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702183952631

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

INDIA: New performance and promotion system

Suchitra Behal
Career advancement prospects in Indian universities became more difficult
last week with the University Grants Commission adopting a
performance-based points system. From now on, lecturers will be graded
annually on their performance and will be eligible for promotions based on
their teaching, research and publication quality =96 not on seniority.=20=
=20
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702183846636

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

INDIA: Single entry test proposed=20

Alya Mishra
With millions of school leavers sitting multiple examinations in their
final year of school, India=92s Education Ministry is proposing a single
national entrance test for universities and professional institutions. The
aim is to reduce student stress and also introduce greater flexibility in a
system that currently makes it difficult for students to switch between
courses once they have made a choice in high school.=20
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702183735557

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

AFRICA: New institute to boost university governance

Jane Marshall
A new institute to strengthen the governance and management of African
universities has been officially inaugurated in Yaound=E9, Cameroon. The
http://www.ipagu.org aims to improve and modernise practices for the
competent running of higher education institutions throughout Sub-Saharan
Africa.=20=20
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702185409730

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

NORWAY: Top bureaucrat claimed false degrees=20

Jan Petter Myklebust
A high-ranking official at the Norwegian Regulation Authority for Health
Personnel has quit following allegations she used fake degrees 15 years ago
to be appointed. Liv L=F8berg, whose husband is the security chief in
Norway=92s parliament, was responsible for authorising the qualifications
each year of hundreds of health professionals, including many foreign
citizens.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D201007021836274

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

FINLAND: New era of private benefactors

Ian R Dobson*
A new universities act has transformed institutions from branches of
government into independent legal entities. Universities now face fewer
restrictions in raising revenue via private donations and bequests.=20
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702183511455

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

AFRICA: Pan-African University close to starting

Gilbert Nganga
Kenya has been selected as the East African host of the planned
Pan-African University, a spec ialised institution comprising a network of
universities that is being created to help supply the continent=92s
high-level human capital. This ends a five-month stalemate between
countries in the region that had been squabbling over who the host would
be.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702185259944

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

EGYPT: University cooperation to ease Nile Basin row

Wagdy Sawahel
Egypt plans to promote higher education cooperation with seven upstream
Nile Basin states in a diplomatic move to strengthen strategic, economic
and cultural relations. The aim is to ease tension sparked by a new pact
calling for equitable water use, which Egypt perceives as being against its
interests.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702185012122

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

AFRICA: International research initiatives launched

Wagdy Sawahel
A number of international initiatives were launched in Africa recently to
develop research and innovation across the continent, and to transform new
ideas generated by higher education and research into improved products,
processes and businesses. The projects include a technology development and
transfer network, a continental research framework programme and a
science-to-business challenge.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702184911821

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

AFRICA: New inventions and discoveries observatory

Wagdy Sawahel
An Online Observatory for African Inventions and Discoveries has been
launched, aimed at encouraging innovation and entrepreneurship to help meet
the continent=92s development challenges.=20
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702184808507
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
NEWSBRIEFS
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CHINA: Future of rapid urbanisation

From critiques of the Shanghai World Expo logo and the expo=92s unsustainab=
le
aftermath, to how changing ideologies and economic regimes are positively
transforming urban spaces, a Global Cities Research Institute at RMIT
University in Melbourne is shining a spotlight on the impact of rapid
urbanisation in China.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702183406403

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Open University hits 20 million iTunes U downloads

The Open University set a world record last week when it became the first
university to achieve 20 million downloaded tracks on iTunes U, a dedicated
area within the http://www.itunes.com/www.iTunes.com.=20
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702183124603

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: OECD launches innovation strategy

The Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Developments has presented
its innovation strategy, focusing on human capital and education. The
initiative was launched at a ministerial council meeting in May following a
three-year multidisciplinary, multi-stakeholder effort, the organisation
announced.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702183035635

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

EUROPE: Research grants top 1,000

Michael Gardner
Professor Erika von Mutius is the thousandth top researcher to receive a
grant from the European Research Council. Von Mutius is exploring new ways
to tackle asthma and allergies. To mark the awarding of the grant, a
ceremony attended by leading figures from the political and research scene
was held in Munich late last month.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182919181
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ACADEMIC FREEDOM
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

IRAN: Prominent scholar released on bail

Roisin Joyce
Emadeddin Baghi, Iranian scholar, journalist and human rights activist,
was released on bail on 23 June. According to reports from
http://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/award-winning-iranian-journalist=
-released-bail-2010-06-23
he was released from Tehran=92s Evin prison on bail of US$200,000 after 180
days in prison.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182807199

More academic freedom reports on the University World News site
CHINA: Publisher scraps Tiananmen Square memoir:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182654738
IRAN: Two UK students in detention in Iran:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182549558
ANGOLA: Professor on trial in Cabinda:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182452722
TURKEY: Education trade unionists on trial:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182347705
RWANDA: American academic released:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182246616
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
SCIENCE SCENE
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

AUSTRALIA: Mutton birds or puffins

Geoff Maslen
Giant tiger snakes as long as a man=92s arm and with heads the size of his
closed fist live on Great Dog Island. So it is always with some trepidation
that La Trobe University researcher Mark Carey pushes his arm down the
burrows where the mutton birds nest =96 in case a tiger is there as well. =
=93I
have a fear of snakes,=94 Carey says. =93And if students are with me on the
island, the one rule is that the =91s=92 word is not to be spoken unless
there=92s one of them about=85=94
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182150182

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Huge prehistoric =91accessories=92 attracted mates=20

Fins, crests and sails =96 various species of dinosaur displayed intriguing
accessories. Now research suggests many of these adaptations grew extra
large in order to attract mates.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702182054939

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Communicating science to the public

A US initiative has tried to find ways to improve communication between
scientists and the public, especially about issues that worry people
deeply. The American Academy of Arts and Sciences project considered how
scientists engage with the public and how their mutual understanding could
be improved.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D201007021819572
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
FEATURES
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: Ivory towers to solar-powered houses=20

Paul Rigg
 The adrenalin buzz among the professors and university students is
palpable during the construction of futuristic structures that run
exclusively on energy generated by the sun. But these are not mere models;
they are real houses that can run everything from washing machines to air
conditioning systems, all from solar power.=20=20
Full report on University World News Website:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702181848949

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

KYRGYZSTAN: University politicisation to continue

Yojana Sharma
The national referendum held in Kyrgyzstan last weekend in the wake of
major unrest in mid-June will not halt the politicisation of universities,
said a Kyrgyz opposition politician in exile who is familiar with the
country=92s universities.
Full report on University World News Website:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702181749676

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

KENYA: Cashing in on foreign language learning

Gilbert Nganga
Kenya=92s universities are rolling out foreign language programmes as
nations and investors, especially from Asia, increasingly turn to the East
African country for resources to boost their industrial growth. In the past
month Kenya=92s biggest universities =96 Nairobi and Kenyatta =96 have anno=
unced
new courses in Korean and Chinese respectively. They both host branches of
China=92s Confucius Institute.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702184658794

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

AFRICA: Does Africa really need new idealism?

Linda Nordling
Perhaps it is a fear that aid from the financially tumultuous North might
be squeezed. Perhaps it is a growing frustration at rich countries=92 failu=
re
to keep their promises to the world=92s poor. Whatever the cause, a wave of
idealism is sweeping through the innovation policy debate, accompanied by
that idealist writ =96 the manifesto.
Full report on University World News Website:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702184546474
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
HE RESEARCH AND COMMENTARY
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: Student disengagement: global comparisons

Jim C=F4t=E9
A common reaction to reports of student disengagement is that we all
should get used to widespread disengagement because nothing better should
be expected from a mass university system. A variety of excuses are made
for students who are =91too busy=92 to put full effort into their studies. =
One
way to approach this =91inevitability question=92 is to ask whether the lev=
els
of student disengagement observed in Canada and the US are also found in
massified systems in other countries.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702181629774

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: Bibliometrics, rankings and transparency

Kristopher Olds*
Why do we care so much about the actual and potential uses of
bibliometrics (=93http://stats.oecd.org/glossary/detail.asp?ID=3D198=94,
according to the OECD) and world university ranking methodologies, but care
so little about the private sector firms, and their inter-firm relations,
that drive the bibliometrics and global rankings agenda forward?
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702181527243

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: Science metrics

The value of scientific output is often measured, to rank one nation
against another, allocate funds between universities, or even grant or deny
tenure. Scientometricians have devised a multitude of =91metrics=92 to help=
 in
these rankings. Do they work? Are they fair? Are they over-used? Nature
investigated this key higher education issue in a
http://www.nature.com/news/specials/metrics/index.html published in its
June edition.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702180036485
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
UNI-LATERAL: Off-beat university stories
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Bees stick to working hours

Bees are often admired by humans for what appears to be a strong work ethic
=96 working throughout the day to gather pollen. But what happens when the
insects have the opportunity to work around the clock? Will they do so?
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100702175928967
